<!-- BEGIN claude-workflow -->
# General Interactions
- In all interactions and commit messages, be extremely concise.
- Sacrifice grammar for the sake of concision. Keep responses as short and direct as possible.

# Planning Workflow
- Whenever generating a plan, explore the codebase first to understand the current structure.
- At the end of EVERY plan, give me a list of "Unresolved Questions" to answer, if any. 
- Make these unresolved questions extremely concise.
- If a task is large, automatically structure the plan as a "multi-phase plan" broken down into sequential implementation steps.

# PRD Breakdown
- Start with ONE infrastructure-only bootstrap issue (deps, CI, build/test config) — no types, no route shells, no domain logic. Let the first vertical slice create the code it needs.
- After bootstrap, every issue must be a vertical slice: a complete user-observable flow crossing all necessary layers (DB → server → client → UI).
- Acceptance criteria describe what the USER sees, not what the code does.
- Each issue must include an integration test that verifies the flow end-to-end.
- Deliver the minimum across all layers to make a flow work — don't gold-plate one layer before touching the next.

Bad (layer-sliced) — each issue tests its layer in isolation, integration bugs hide until the end:

  E-commerce app:
    - "Build product DB schema + queries"
    - "Build cart state management"
    - "Build checkout API endpoint"
    - "Build checkout UI page"

  Chat app:
    - "Build message model + DB layer"
    - "Build WebSocket message handler"
    - "Build chat UI component"

  Dashboard app:
    - "Build analytics API endpoints"
    - "Build chart components"
    - "Build filter/date-range state"

Good (flow-sliced) — each issue delivers a complete user behavior across all layers:

  E-commerce app:
    - "User adds item to cart and sees updated cart count"
      - Touches: product API, cart state, UI badge
      - AC: "User clicks Add to Cart → cart icon shows '1' → page refresh preserves cart"
      - Integration test: API call → state update → UI render → persistence check

    - "User completes checkout and receives confirmation"
      - Touches: cart, payment API, order DB, confirmation UI
      - AC: "User clicks Pay → payment processed → order stored → confirmation page shown"
      - Integration test: submit order → verify payment call → verify DB row → verify redirect

  Chat app:
    - "User sends message and recipient sees it in real-time"
      - Touches: input UI, WS handler, message store, recipient's message list
      - AC: "User A types message → hits send → User B sees it appear without refresh"
      - Integration test: send via WS → verify server stores → verify broadcast → verify recipient UI

    - "User reconnects after network drop and sees missed messages"
      - AC: "User goes offline → messages arrive → user reconnects → missed messages appear in order"
      - Integration test: disconnect → send messages → reconnect → verify message backfill

  Dashboard app:
    - "User filters by date range and sees updated charts"
      - Touches: filter UI, API query params, chart rendering
      - AC: "User selects 'Last 7 days' → charts update with filtered data → URL reflects filter"
      - Integration test: select filter → verify API called with params → verify chart data matches

# Execution & Git/GitHub Workflow
- Your primary method for interacting with GitHub should be the GitHub CLI (gh).
- Always create a feature branch before implementing changes.
- After implementation is complete, commit, push, and create a PR for human review.
<!-- END claude-workflow -->
